{
  "doc_id": "13500",
  "text": "Toll-like receptors (TLRs) are receptors of the innate immune response that are involved in detection and response to pathogen-associated molecules such as lipopolysaccharide [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , bacterial lipoproteins [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , bacterial flagellin (2, 30), and unmethylated CpG DNA [CITATION_10] . In previous studies, Toll-like receptors were found to be critical in the host response to the related tissue-associated pathogen B. burgdorferi [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] and in response to blood-borne pathogens such as group B streptococcus [CITATION_16] . Others have predicted that recognition and signaling by the variable-surface lipoproteins expressed by relapsing fever Borrelia is involved in the inflammatory and febrile responses during bacteremic episodes [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] . TLR signaling also has a significant role in host defense to numerous pathogens [CITATION_19] [CITATION_20] [CITATION_21] [CITATION_22] [CITATION_23] . The experiments presented in this report reveal that TLR signaling is important in two aspects of host response to B. hermsii: the rapid antibody production against B. hermsii lipoproteins and an antibody-independent entity required for clearance of blood-borne B. hermsii.",
